      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Courts determine fundamental rights by looking at historical tradition and deeply ingrained societal values, not by simply inventing new rights. When a right is deemed \"fundamental,\" it means the government must meet a very high level of scrutiny to justify any infringement upon it. This rigorous standard ensures that the protection afforded by substantive due process is reserved for the most essential liberties of the individual.",
      "source": "target",
